T1  - Voluntary Precision Disclosure and Endogenous Market Feedback
AU  - Schneemeier, Jan
Y1  - 2022/10/18
PY  - 2022
DA  - 2023/09/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.2022.4577
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.2022.4577
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 5618
EP  - 5637
VL  - 69
IS  - 9
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - We explore a manager?s incentives to disclose the precision of a signal about firm profitability. Voluntary disclosure of precision information encourages traders to acquire private information, increasing price informativeness and improving the firm?s investment efficiency. We highlight a novel tradeoff: on the one hand, more precise public information crowds out traders? information acquisition by leveling the playing field. On the other hand, there can also be a crowding-in effect because high-precision disclosures indicate greater managerial confidence and higher investment, which increases the traders? value of information. The crowding-in effect can dominate if the firm discloses above-average profitability. We derive testable predictions regarding the financial market consequences of supplemental disclosures that are informative about the precision or relevance of payoff-related signals.This paper was accepted by Brian Bushee, accounting.
AB  - We explore a manager?s incentives to disclose the precision of a signal about firm profitability. Voluntary disclosure of precision information encourages traders to acquire private information, increasing price informativeness and improving the firm?s investment efficiency. We highlight a novel tradeoff: on the one hand, more precise public information crowds out traders? information acquisition by leveling the playing field. On the other hand, there can also be a crowding-in effect because high-precision disclosures indicate greater managerial confidence and higher investment, which increases the traders? value of information. The crowding-in effect can dominate if the firm discloses above-average profitability. We derive testable predictions regarding the financial market consequences of supplemental disclosures that are informative about the precision or relevance of payoff-related signals.This paper was accepted by Brian Bushee, accounting.
